As of my last knowledge update in October 2023, Google Maps does not provide a specific "time travel" API endpoint in the way that one might find in fictional storytelling. However, the concept of "time travel" in the context of Google Maps often refers to viewing historical satellite imagery or street views, which Google provides through its Google Maps API.

While there's no direct API for "time traveling" specifically, you can access historical imagery and street views to some extent using the appropriate Google Maps services. Below is an example code snippet for using the Google Maps JavaScript API to display a street view image at a specific location with historical imagery.

### Example Code to Access Street View
To use the Google Maps JavaScript API to view Street View, you'll need an API key. Replace `"YOUR_API_KEY"` with your actual Google Maps API key.

1. **Set up your HTML:**
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Street View with Google Maps API</title>
    <script src="https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/js?key=YOUR_API_KEY"></script>
    <style>
      #map {
        height: 400px;
        width: 100%;
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h3>Google Maps Street View</h3>
    <div id="map"></div>
    <script>
      function initMap() {
        const fenway = { lat: 42.347573, lng: -71.097219 };

        const panorama = new google.maps.StreetViewPanorama(
          document.getElementById("map"),
          {
            position: fenway,
            pov: {
              heading: 165,
              pitch: 0,
            },
            zoom: 1,
          }
        );

        // Note: Google Maps API doesn't directly allow querying historical street view images.
        // You might need to look for historical images in Google Maps itself.
      }
      initMap();
    </script>
  </body>
</html>
```

2. **Historical Data Access:**
While you can access current Street View data easily, Google does not provide a direct way to query historical imagery through its public APIs. You can view historical imagery in Google Earth Pro, which has more features for viewing past satellite imagery.

